Tweet Thread

Tweet One

Hi Argo community! I want to introduce you to a newly developed package R package, argoFloats. This package was created by myself, Dan Kelley, and Jaimie Harbin to provide tools for downloading and analyzing collections of oceanographic Argo float datasets.

Insert argoFloats logo

Tweet Two

argoFloats has an easy-to-follow work flow, to allow the users to effectively access, download, and read Argo data.

Figure 1: Work flow of the argoFloats package.

Tweet Three

To get familiar with argoFloats, check out the user website, https://argocanada.github.io/argoFloats/index.html, or developer website https://github.com/ArgoCanada/argoFloats for more advanced R users.

Tweet Four

A series of real-time examples exists at our youtube channel https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCmVBNwRRGx5sRa1skvfOrvA, which include some East coast humour to enjoy.

Tweet Five

The following code produces a TS plot near Bermuda:

library(argoFloats) ai <- getIndex() ais <- subset(ai, circle=list(longitude=-64.7505, latitude=32.3078, radius=50)) pr <- getProfiles(ais) a <- readProfiles(pr, handleFlags = TRUE) plot(a, which=“TS”)

Tweet Six
